Cheung Kong, China Yurun, New World: Hong Kong Equities Preview

-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 
2011-09-26T01:04:28Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-26/cheung-kong-china-yurun-new-world-hong-kong-equities-preview.html
The following companies may have
significant price changes in  Hong Kong  trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  fell 1.4 percent to 17,668.83. The Hang
Seng  China  Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H shares of
Chinese companies, declined 1.8 percent to 9,033.09.  Chinese property developers: Some small and medium-sized
Chinese developers with an over-extended balance sheets face
bankruptcy in coming months as sales slow and the government
tightens control on loans from trust companies, UBS AG said.  Separately, China’s southwestern city of Chongqing will
impose a property tax on owners of villas from Oct. 1, becoming
the first Chinese city to tax existing homes, China Business
News reported, citing an unidentified local tax bureau official.  Agile Property Holdings Ltd. (3383)  (3383 HK), a builder of villas
and apartments in China’s Guangdong province, rose 2.4 percent
to HK$6.05.  Country Garden Holdings Co. (2007)  (2007 HK), a developer
that receives all its sales from the mainland, declined 2.3
percent to HK$2.16.  Hong Kong property developers: The number of used-home
transactions in 10 of Hong Kong’s biggest private developments
fell from a week earlier amid homebuyers’ concern over slowing
global economic growth.  The number of deals recorded on Sept. 24 and 25 in projects
including Tai Koo Shing and Mei Foo Sun Chuen dropped to 10 from
22 a week earlier, Centaline Property Agency Ltd., Hong Kong’s
biggest closely held realtor, said in an e-mailed statement
yesterday.  Sun Hung Kai Properties Ltd. (16)  (16 HK), the world’s biggest
developer by market value, fell 3 percent to HK$93.50.  Cheung Kong  (Holdings) Ltd. (1 HK), controlled by
billionaire  Li Ka-shing , retreated 1 percent to HK$88.60. Li Ka-
shing bought 340,000 shares of the company at an average
HK$93.77 each on Sept. 21, according to a filing to the Hong
Kong stock exchange.  Brightoil Petroleum Holdings Ltd. (933)  (933 HK): The provider of
marine bunkering services business said full-year net income
rose to HK$1.27 billion ($163 million) from HK$1.11 billion a
year earlier. The stock fell 3.1 percent to HK$1.89.  China Communications Construction Co. (1800 HK): The port
builder may raise as much as 20 billion yuan ($3.1 billion) in
its first share sale in Shanghai, for which the company hasn’t
set a date. The company plans to issue as many as 3.5 billion
new shares, according to a filing to the China Securities
Regulatory Commission. The stock increased 1.2 percent to
HK$5.07.  China Yurun Food Group Ltd. (1068)  (1068 HK): The meat processor
said it expects third-quarter profit to decrease from the same
period a year earlier because of “negative” media reports and
an increase in raw material costs. The stock tumbled 11 percent
to HK$10.88.  New World Development Co. (17 HK): Blackstone Group LP, the
a private-equity firm, agreed to sell its 95 percent stake in
Shanghai’s Channel 1 shopping mall to New World Development Co.
in Hong Kong for 1.46 billion yuan, according to three people
briefed on the transaction. The stock slid 2 percent to HK$7.68.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Kana Nishizawa in Hong Kong at 
 knishizawa5@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at 
 ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 